<p>The <b>knot</b> (<span class=3D"rt-commentedText nowrap"><span class=3D"=
IPA nopopups noexcerpt" lang=3D"en-fonipa"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Help:IPA/English" title=3D"Help:IPA/English">/<span style=3D"borde=
r-bottom:1px dotted"><span title=3D"'n' in 'nigh'">n</span><span title=3D"/=
=C9=92/: 'o' in 'body'">=C9=92</span><span title=3D"'t' in 'tie'">t</span><=
/span>/</a></span></span>) is a unit of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Speed" title=3D"Speed">speed</a> equal to one <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Nautical_mile" title=3D"Nautical mile">nautical mile</a> =
per hour, exactly <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"699951444=
4444444444=E2=99=A0"></span>1.852&nbsp;km/h</span> (approximately <span cla=
ss=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6999514543039999999=E2=99=A0"></span=
>1.151&nbsp;mph</span> or <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"6=
999514000000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>0.514&nbsp;m/s</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(u=
nit)#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-2"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_80000-3" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"ISO 80000-3">ISO standard</a> symbol for the knot is <b>kn</b=
>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<=
span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The same symbol is preferred=
 by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Institute_of_Electrical_an=
d_Electronics_Engineers" title=3D"Institute of Electrical and Electronics E=
ngineers">Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers</a> (IEEE), whi=
le <b>kt</b> is also common, especially in aviation, where it is the form r=
ecommended by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Ci=
vil_Aviation_Organization" title=3D"International Civil Aviation Organizati=
on">International Civil Aviation Organization</a> (ICAO).<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(uni=
t)#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> The knot is a non-<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/International_System_of_Units" title=3D"International System of =
Units">SI</a> unit.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nonSi_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-nonSi-5"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The knot is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meteorology=
" title=3D"Meteorology">meteorology</a>, and in <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Maritime_transport" title=3D"Maritime transport">maritime</a>=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aviation" title=3D"Aviation">=
air</a> navigation. A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Watercraft" =
title=3D"Watercraft">vessel</a> travelling at 1&nbsp;knot along a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Meridian_(geography)" title=3D"Meridian (=
geography)">meridian</a> travels approximately one <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Minute_and_second_of_arc" title=3D"Minute and second of ar=
c">minute</a> of geographic <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latitu=
de" title=3D"Latitude">latitude</a> in one hour.
</p>
