<dl><dt>1 international knot =3D</dt>
<dd>1&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautical_mile" title=3D=
"Nautical mile">nautical mile</a> per <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Hour" title=3D"Hour">hour</a> (by definition),</dd>
<dd><span style=3D"white-space: nowrap">1<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em=
">852.000</span></span> metres per hour (exactly),<sup id=3D"cite_ref-nonSi=
_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(un=
it)#cite_note-nonSi-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup></dd>
<dd>0.51444 metres per second (approximately),</dd>
<dd>1.15078 miles per hour (approximately),</dd>
<dd>20.25372 inches per second (approximately)</dd>
<dd>1.68781 feet per second (approximately).</dd></dl>
<p>The length of the internationally agreed nautical mile is <span class=3D=
"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003185200000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>1<sp=
an style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">852</span>&nbsp;m</span>. The US adopted th=
e international definition in 1954, having previously used the US nautical =
mile (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003185324800000000=
=E2=99=A0"></span>1<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">853</span>.248&nbsp;m=
</span>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-usnm_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-usnm-6"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The UK ad=
opted the international nautical mile definition in 1970, having previously=
 used the UK <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_Admiralty" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"British Admiralty">Admiralty</a> nautical mile=
 (<span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003185318400000000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>6<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">080</span>&nbsp;ft</span> o=
r <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7003185318400000000=E2=99=
=A0"></span>1<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">853</span>.184&nbsp;m</span=
>).
</p>
