</p><div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Usage">Usage</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKnot_(unit)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Usage"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The speeds of vehicles relative to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fluid" title=3D"Fluid">fluids</a> in which they travel (boat speeds=
 and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_speed" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Air speed">air speeds</a>) can be measured in knots. For consi=
stency, the speeds of navigational fluids (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Ocean_current" title=3D"Ocean current">ocean currents</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tidal_stream_(marine_science)" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Tidal stream (marine science)">tidal streams</a>, <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/River_current" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"River current">river currents</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Wind_speed" title=3D"Wind speed">wind speeds</a>) are also mea=
sured in knots. Thus, speed over the ground (SOG; <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Ground_speed" title=3D"Ground speed">ground speed</a> (GS) =
in aircraft) and rate of progress towards a distant point ("<a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Velocity_made_good" title=3D"Velocity made good">=
velocity made good</a>", VMG) can also be given in knots. Since 1979, the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_Civil_Aviation_Organi=
zation" title=3D"International Civil Aviation Organization">International C=
ivil Aviation Organization</a> list the knot as permitted for temporary use=
 in aviation, but no end date to the temporary period has been agreed as of=
 2024<sup class=3D"plainlinks noexcerpt noprint asof-tag update" style=3D"d=
isplay:none;"><a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
/index.php?title=3DKnot_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit">[update]</a></sup>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Origin">Origin</h2><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKnot_(unit)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Origin"><span>edit</span></=
a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Until the mid-19th century, vessel speed at sea was measured using a <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chip_log" title=3D"Chip log">chip log=
</a>. This consisted of a wooden panel, attached by line to a reel, and wei=
ghted on one edge to float perpendicularly to the water surface and thus pr=
esent substantial resistance to the water moving around it. The chip log wa=
s cast over the stern of the moving vessel and the line allowed to pay out.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Abbott1858_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-Abbott1858-8"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot" title=3D"Knot">Knots</a> tied at a=
 distance of 47&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)" =
title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a> 3&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Inch" title=3D"Inch">inches</a> (14.4018&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">m</a>) from each other, passed throu=
gh a sailor's fingers, while another sailor used a 30-second <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hourglass" title=3D"Hourglass">sand-glass</a> (2=
8-second sand-glass is the currently accepted timing) to time the operation=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The knot count would be repor=
ted and used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sailing_master=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sailing master">sailing master</a>'s <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_reckoning" title=3D"Dead reckoning=
">dead reckoning</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Navigatio=
n" title=3D"Navigation">navigation</a>.=20
</p><p>This method gives a value for the knot of <span class=3D"frac">20<sp=
an class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span cla=
ss=3D"den">4</span></span> inches per second or 1.85166 kilometres per hour=
. The difference from the modern definition is less than 0.02%.
</p><p>Derivation of knots spacing:
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=
