<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Modern_use">Modern use</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DKnot_(unit)&amp;=
action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Modern use"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:World_Scale_from_DMA_Series_1150_map.png" cla=
ss=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikiped=
ia/commons/thumb/2/25/World_Scale_from_DMA_Series_1150_map.png/250px-World_=
Scale_from_DMA_Series_1150_map.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=
=3D"67" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"3301" data-file-height=
=3D"890"></a><figcaption>Graphic scale from a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Mercator_projection" title=3D"Mercator projection">Mercator pro=
jection</a> world map, showing the change with latitude</figcaption></figur=
e>
<p>Although the unit <i>knot</i> does not fit within the SI system, its ret=
ention for nautical and aviation use is important because the length of a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nautical_mile" title=3D"Nautical mi=
le">nautical mile</a>, upon which the knot is based, is closely related to =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Longitude" title=3D"Longitude"=
>longitude</a>/<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latitude" title=3D"=
Latitude">latitude</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geographic_=
coordinate_system" title=3D"Geographic coordinate system">geographic coordi=
nate system</a>. As a result, nautical miles and knots are convenient units=
 to use when navigating an aircraft or ship.
</p><p>On a standard nautical chart using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Mercator_projection" title=3D"Mercator projection">Mercator project=
ion</a>, the horizontal (East=E2=80=93West) scale varies with latitude. On =
a chart of the North Atlantic, the scale varies by a factor of two from Flo=
rida to Greenland. A single <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear=
_scale" title=3D"Linear scale">graphic scale</a>, of the sort on many maps,=
 would therefore be useless on such a chart. Since the length of a nautical=
 mile, for practical purposes, is equivalent to about a minute of latitude,=
 a distance in nautical miles on a chart can easily be measured by using <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caliper#Divider_caliper" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Caliper">dividers</a> and the latitude scales on the si=
des of the chart. Recent British <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
dmiralty_chart" title=3D"Admiralty chart">Admiralty charts</a> have a latit=
ude scale down the middle to make this even easier.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#ci=
te_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Speed is sometimes incorrectly expressed as "knots per hour",<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-Kipling_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-Kipling-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which would mean=
 "nautical miles per hour per hour" and thus would refer to <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acceleration" title=3D"Acceleration">acceleration=
</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Aeronautical_terms">Aeronau=
tical terms</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Knot_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Aeron=
autical terms"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Prior to 1969, airworthiness standards for civil aircraft in the United =
States <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federal_Aviation_Regulation=
s" title=3D"Federal Aviation Regulations">Federal Aviation Regulations</a> =
specified that distances were to be in statute miles, and speeds in miles p=
er hour. In 1969, these standards were progressively amended to specify tha=
t distances were to be in nautical miles, and speeds in knots.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kno=
t_(unit)#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The following abbreviations are used to distinguish between various =
measurements of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airspeed" title=3D=
"Airspeed">airspeed</a>:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knot_(unit)#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<ul><li>TAS is "knots <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/True_airspee=
d" title=3D"True airspeed">true airspeed</a>", the airspeed of an aircraft =
relative to undisturbed air</li>
<li>KIAS is "knots <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indicated_airsp=
eed" title=3D"Indicated airspeed">indicated airspeed</a>", the speed shown =
on an aircraft's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pitot-static_syst=
em" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pitot-static system">pitot-static</a> <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Airspeed_indicator" title=3D"Airspee=
d indicator">airspeed indicator</a></li>
<li>CAS is "knots <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calibrated_airsp=
eed" title=3D"Calibrated airspeed">calibrated airspeed</a>", the indicated =
airspeed corrected for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Position_er=
ror" title=3D"Position error">position error</a> and instrument error</li>
<li>EAS is "knots <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Equivalent_airsp=
eed" title=3D"Equivalent airspeed">equivalent airspeed</a>", the calibrated=
 airspeed corrected for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adiabatic_=
process" title=3D"Adiabatic process">adiabatic</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Compressible_flow" title=3D"Compressible flow">compressibl=
e flow</a> for the particular altitude</li></ul>
<p>The indicated airspeed is close to the true airspeed only at sea level i=
n standard conditions and at low speeds. At <span style=3D"white-space: now=
rap">11<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">000</span></span>&nbsp;m (<span =
style=3D"white-space: nowrap">36<span style=3D"margin-left: 0.25em">000</sp=
an></span>&nbsp;ft), an indicated airspeed of 300 kn may correspond to a tr=
ue airspeed of 500 kn in standard conditions.
</p>
